The paper deals with algorithmic and economic challenges in combinatorial market design problems, which are typically studied in the field of computational game theory (cs.GT). The paper also introduces a new concept called Market-Clearing Combinatorial Walrasian Equilibrium (MC-CWE), which is a relaxation of the classical Walrasian equilibrium (WE) solution concept. This concept is related to the study of algorithms for optimization problems, which falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the design of computationally efficient mechanisms that generate MC-CWE outcomes, which is a problem in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and computational economics (cs.EC). Finally, the paper provides tight welfare approximation results for a variety of valuation classes, which is related to the study of machine learning and optimization (cs.LG).
